<topic class="Popup" template="Default" status="Under Construction" lasteditedby="Adam" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:noNamespaceSchemaLocation="../../../helpproject.xsd">
  <title translate="true">Maximum Shear Stress</title>
  <keywords>
    <keyword translate="true">Maximum Contact Shear Stress</keyword>
    <keyword translate="true">Metal Fatigue</keyword>
  </keywords>
  <body>
    <para styleclass="Popup Box"><table styleclass="PopupTable" rowcount="1" colcount="1">
      <tr style="vertical-align:top">
        <td>
          <para styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" style="margin-left:0px;"><text styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" translate="true">The </text><text styleclass="Popup Box2" translate="true">Maximum Contact Shear Stress</text><text styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" translate="true"> is important for calculating the Fatigue Life of 2D Cams and Cam-Followers. </text></para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" style="margin-left:0px;"><text styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" translate="true">See Cam Mechanisms &gt; Cam Analysis and Checklist.</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Normal"><line style="height:1px; color:#ff6600;"/></para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text2-Note"><text styleclass="Body Text2-Note" translate="true">The &apos;Maximum Shear Stress&apos; is slightly below the Cam surface. Its maximum value is a function of a number of parameters: Radius-of-Curvature of the Cam-Follower and the Cam, Material properties of the Cam and Cam-Follower (Young&apos;s Modulus and Poison&apos;s Ratio - see </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="MD-Dialog-2D-Cam" styleclass="Body Text2-Note" translate="true">2D-Cam dialog-box</link><text styleclass="Body Text2-Note" translate="true">) the Contact Force between the Cam and Cam-Follower.</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Normal"><line style="height:1px; color:#ff6600;"/></para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" style="margin-left:0px;"><text styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" translate="true">There are some assumptions:</text></para>
          <list id="3" type="ol" listtype="decimal" formatstring="%0:s." format-charset="DEFAULT_CHARSET" levelreset="true" legalstyle="false" startfrom="1" styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:10pt; color:#000000;">
            <li styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2"><text styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" translate="true">The width of the 2D-Cam is the same as the Extrusion Depth of the Cam-Follower Profile. </text></li>
            <li styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2"><text styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" translate="true">The 2D-Cam and Cam-Follower are &apos;Isotropic&apos;. </text></li>
            <li styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2"><text styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" translate="true">The 2D-Cam and Cam-Follower are &apos;Linearly Elastic&apos;.</text></li>
            <li styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2"><text styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" translate="true">The dimensions of the contact area are very small in comparison with the radii of the un-deformed bodies in the vicinity of the contact.</text></li>
            <li styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2"><text styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" translate="true">The shape of the deformed surfaces adjacent to the contact zone is a rectangle. </text></li>
            <li styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2"><text styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" translate="true">At the contact interface, the bodies are approximately flat.</text></li>
            <li styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2"><text styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" translate="true">The bodies are </text><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true">frictionless</text><text styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" translate="true">; only normal stresses arising during contact are considered. Relative displacements in the X and Y directions are neglected. Add about 30% if Cam Rollers are not used without an oil bath.</text></li>
            <li styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2"><text styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" translate="true">The surfaces are free from surface debris and not lubricated.</text></li>
          </list>
          <para styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" style="margin-left:0px;"><text styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" translate="true">See also: </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="MD-Cam-MaxShearStress-equations" styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" translate="true">Equations to calculate Maximum Contact Shear Stress</link><text styleclass="Body Text - bit bit bigger2" translate="true">.</text></para>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </table></para>
  </body>
</topic>
